Problem:
Two circles have the same center $C.$ (Circles which have the same center are called concentric.) The larger circle has radius $10$ and the smaller circle has radius $6.$ Determine the area of the ring between these two circles. [asy]
import graph;
filldraw(circle((0,0),10), lightgray, black+linewidth(1));
filldraw(circle((0,0),6), white, black+linewidth(1));
dot((0,0));
label("$C$",(0,0),NE);
[/asy]

Problem:
The figure shown represents a plot of land and is drawn using a scale in which 1 cm equals 2 miles. One square mile is 640 acres. How large is the actual plot of land, in acres? [asy]
draw((0,0)--(15,0)--(10,10)--(0,10)--cycle);
draw((0,1)--(1,1)--(1,0));
draw((0,9)--(1,9)--(1,10));
label("15 cm",(7.5,0),S);
label("10 cm",(0,5),W);
label("10 cm",(5,10),N);
[/asy]

generated_answer:
The plot of land is a right trapezoid with bases 10 miles and 6 miles, and height 15 miles.  The area of the plot of land is thus \begin{align*}
\frac{(10+6)(15)}{2} \cdot 640 &= 16 \cdot 15 \cdot 640\\
&= 153,600 \text{ acres}.
\end{align*}Since 1 cm represents 2 miles, 15 cm represents 30 miles.  Therefore, we have $1\text{ cm}^2 = (2\text{ miles})^2 = 4\text{ miles}^2$.  Since the area of the plot of land is $153,\!600$ acres, we have \begin{align*}
\text{area} &= 153,\!600 \text{ acres} \cdot \frac{1\text{ cm}^2}{4\text{ miles}^2} \\
&= 153,\!600 \cdot \frac{1}{4} \cdot \frac{1}{2.54^2} \text{ cm}^2 \\
&\approx \boxed{9.9 \text{ million acres}}.
\end{align*}

